{{afc comment|1=Page originally made on english wikipedia in draftspace. g13 deleted and archived on everybodywiki. Go to [[:en:Wikipedia:Requests for undeletion]] to request undeletion of original page [[:en:draft:Narita-san Temple]] and import the revisions to here for attribution. View on everybodywiki here [[:every:Narita-san Temple|Narita-san Temple]]. [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 21:01, 16 February 2025 (UTC)}}
{{draft}} {{Promising draft|reason=the high amount of work put into it over a long time, see edit history}}
{{日本の寺院 |名称 = 成田山名古屋別院大聖寺 |image = [[File:Partial view of Daishoji Staircase.jpg|300px]] |所在地 = 愛知県犬山市犬山北白山平5番地 | 緯度度 = 35|緯度分 = 23|緯度秒 = 20.76 | 経度度 = 136|経度分 = 56|経度秒 = 57.23 |地図 = Japan#Japan Aichi |山号 = 成田山 |宗旨 = |宗派 = [[真言宗智山派]] |寺格 = |本尊 = [[不動明王]] |創建年 = [[1953]] |開山 = |開基 = |中興年 = |中興 = |正式名 = |別称 = |札所等 = |文化財 = |公式HP = http://www.inuyama-naritasan.or.jp/ |公式HP名 = 犬山成田山 }} [[File:Hatsumōde in Inuyama Naritasan No - 4.jpg|thumb|250px|''[[Hatsumōde]]'' at {{ill|Narita-san Temple|ja|成田山名古屋別院大聖寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[Inuyama, Aichi]]]] {{ill|Narita-san Temple|ja|成田山名古屋別院大聖寺|12=draft|12=draft}} is a [[Buddhist temple]] in [[Inuyama, Aichi]].
It is a branch temple of [[Narita-san]] '''Naritasan Nagoya Betsuin Daishoji''' (成田山名古屋別院大聖寺) is a {{ill|Shingon Chizan Sect|ja|真言宗智山派|1=Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|12=draft|12=draft}} temple located in {{ill|Inuyama, Aichi|ja|犬山市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is a branch temple of {{ill|Naritasan Shinshoji|ja|成田山新勝寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Narita, Chiba|ja|成田市|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="tabi">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://inuyama-tabi.com/data/download/100/8/inuyamahigashi.pdf |title=犬山たび 巻之二 犬山東編 |access-date=2024-9-16 |publisher=犬山市教育委員会|page=15}}</ref> Commonly referred to as "'''Inuyama Naritasan'''".<ref name="tabi" />
== Overview == A "Dedication Association" was formed in {{ill|1936|ja|1936th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft}} 11) due to the long distance required for pilgrimage to Shinshoji. However, the temple was not officially established until {{ill|1953|ja|1953rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōwa 28) after World War II.
The founding of the temple was primarily supported by {{ill|Nagoya Railroad|ja|名古屋鉄道|12=draft|12=draft}} (Meitetsu) and its group companies, which contributed donations. Due to this association, amulets from the temple, praying for traffic safety, are placed near the driver's seat in Meitetsu trains and {{ill|Meitetsu Bus|ja|名鉄バス|12=draft|12=draft}} vehicles. Additional financial support came from {{ill|Matsuzakaya|ja|松坂屋|12=draft|12=draft}} and other business leaders in central Japan.
The temple is especially known for granting blessings for traffic safety and is commonly referred to as a "traffic safety temple." The principal deity is {{ill|Fudō Myō-ō|ja|不動明王|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Temple Complex == * Main Hall * Prayer Hall (Kaji-do) * Kōbō Hall * Seiran Hall * Myōō Gate
== Grounds == Due to disturbances caused by loud vehicles and motorcycles, entry into the temple grounds at night has been prohibited since {{ill|September 15, 2024|ja|2024th year 9月15日|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.chunichi.co.jp/article/957659 |title=境内に爆音車続々…「犬山成田山」が苦渋の決断、夜間の立ち入り禁止へ |access-date=2024-9-16 |publisher=中日新聞}}</ref>
The temple grounds previously housed {{ill|Naritasan Station|ja|成田山駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Meitetsu Monkey Park Monorail Line|ja|名鉄モンキーパークモノレール線|12=draft|12=draft}}, but the station was closed on {{ill|December 27, 2008|ja|2008th year 12月27日|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft|12=draft}} 20).
== Major Annual Events == * {{ill|Hatsu Fudō|ja|初不動|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Setsubun Festival|ja|節分まつり|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Star Festival|ja|星まつり|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Kanbutsu-e|ja|灌仏会|12=draft|12=draft}} (Flower Festival) * {{ill|Bon Festival|ja|お盆|12=draft|12=draft}} Memorial Lantern Dedication * Great Exorcism Prayer Ceremony * {{ill|Shichi-Go-San|ja|七五三|12=draft|12=draft}} Celebration * Founding Anniversary Grand Festival * Year-End Fudō Ceremony
== Gallery == {{gallery |File:View of Daishoji while climing the staircase.jpg|Myōō Gate |File:Inuyama Naritasan Hondō.jpg|Main Hall |File:Daishouji3.JPG|View from the Main Hall |File:Inuyama Castle from daishoji.jpg|View of {{ill|Inuyama Castle|ja|犬山城|12=draft|12=draft}} from the Main Hall }}
== Access == * {{ill|Nagoya Railroad|ja|名古屋鉄道|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Meitetsu Inuyama Line|ja|名鉄犬山線|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Meitetsu Hiromi Line|ja|名鉄広見線|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Meitetsu Komaki Line|ja|名鉄小牧線|12=draft|12=draft}} - 10-15 minute walk from {{ill|Inuyama Station|ja|犬山駅|12=draft|12=draft}}. * 5-minute walk from {{ill|Inuyama Yūen Station|ja|犬山遊園駅|12=draft|12=draft}}. * Free large parking lot (600 cars available).
== Notes == A training facility for {{ill|Tokiwayama Stable|ja|時津風部屋|12=draft|12=draft}}, associated with the {{ill|Nagoya Tournament|ja|名古屋場所|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Professional Sumo|ja|大相撲|12=draft|12=draft}}, is located on the temple grounds near the former Naritasan Station site. On {{ill|June 26, 2007|ja|2007th year 6月26日|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Tokitsukaze Stable Scandal|ja|時津風部屋力士暴行死事件|12=draft|12=draft}} occurred here, where a 17-year-old sumo apprentice suffered fatal injuries during training.
== Temple History == * Daishoji 30-Year History Compilation Committee (1984). "Daishoji 30-Year History." Naritasan Nagoya Betsuin. == See Also == * {{ill|Naritasan Shinshoji|ja|成田山新勝寺|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Naritasan Tokyo Betsuin Fukagawa Fudōdō|ja|成田山東京別院深川不動堂|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Naritasan Osaka Betsuin Myōō-in|ja|成田山大阪別院明王院|12=draft|12=draft}} – Donated by {{ill|Keihan Electric Railway|ja|京阪電気鉄道|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Sayama Fudōson|ja|狭山不動尊|12=draft|12=draft}} – Donated by {{ill|Seibu Railway Group|ja|西武鉄道グループ|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Teishō-ji|ja|貞照寺|12=draft|12=draft}} – Managed under Naritasan Nagoya Betsuin. * {{ill|Shinya Azukibata|ja|小豆畑眞也|12=draft|12=draft}} – Former professional baseball player. His father is a monk at Daishoji.
== External Links == {{Commonscat|Daishoji (Inuyama)}} * [http://www.inuyama-naritasan.or.jp/ Official Naritasan Nagoya Betsuin Website]
